richard white the bill lane center for the american west stanford university school of humanities & sciences home contact about people directors and staff advisory council former researchers faculty committee research projects fellowships for students courses on the west events publications home people richard white richard white richard white faculty co director 2002 present margaret byrne professor of american history email whiter stanford edu biography publications richard white the margaret byrne professor of american history is widely regarded as one of the nation's leading scholars in three related fields the american west native american history and environmental history professor white came to stanford in 1998 he is the author of five books including the middle ground indians empires and republic in the great lakes region 1650 1815 which was named a finalist for the 1992 pulitzer prize among other honors he is the recipient of a macarthur foundation fellowship he received an ab in history from the university of california santa cruz and an ma and phd from the university of washington professor white's areas of study include the american northwest including canada with wide interests in social environmental and cultural cross currents white's first book land use environment and social change in a western county island county washington 1790 1940 was one of the first small scale studies of ecological change produced by environmental historians professor white is also the principal investigator for the shaping the west project within the spatial history project this project explores the construction of space by transcontinental railroads in north america during the late nineteenth century a key theme in his forthcoming book railroaded the transcontinentals and the making of modern america norton may 2011 publications video david m kennedy and richard white discuss myths of the transcontinental railroad book railroaded the transcontinentals and the making of mod